post_text:
Thank you to LIXIL Americas for their generous donation of 120 face shields for use in our Branchburg schools!

Knowing there was an urgent need for PPE, @lixilamericasofficial repurposed their 3D printers to make face shields and then located people in need at first focusing on hospitals and others in the healthcare community.

The Piscataway based company is donating 50,000 face shields across the country to aid COVID-19 response efforts!

Today, 3rd grade students at Whiton and their families were invited to join staff members for a wave parade!

Whiton staff members lined the sidewalk in front of Whiton, to wave and send-off our third graders who will be attending Stony Brook School next school year.

Many of our 3rd grade families joined the celebration and decorated their cars, honked their horns and waved so long to their teachers!

8th grade BCMS GATE students are hosting GATE DATE 2020: Optimistic Olympics, a week long virtual challenge, May 20-May 29. Our students spent six weeks redesigning their event to go online for GATE students in grades 1-7.

As an enrichment opportunity for any students who want a challenge, Optimistic Olympics activities will also be posted in the BCMS Contest Classroom, code: noxnotk, starting June 1.

No teams, no judging, just fun creative challenges!

In Mr. Boehm’s art class at Whiton, students were asked to create a tree collage using found objects in nature. They began by drawing the trunk of a tree on a piece of paper. Then, instead of drawing the branches, leaves and flowers, they were encouraged to go out into nature and find real life objects to incorporate into their artwork.

Hope you enjoy their creations!

Every year, the BCMS girls ensemble 7 O'Clock Harmony, sings for our Teachers and Educational Specialists of the Year at a celebratory Board meeting. In spite of our current circumstances, we still wanted to pay tribute not only to these outstanding staff members, but to all of the staff throughout Branchburg Township School District.

We hope you enjoy our teacher appreciation song, entitled "You Have Made a Difference".

Thank you for all that you do!

At Whiton, Mr. Boehm’s art students spent the past two weeks focusing on "creating art from nature.”

2nd and 3rd grade students were asked to find objects in nature and organize them in a way that creates a visually interesting pattern. They were also encouraged to incorporate rhythm and repetition into their design to make their art more interesting. Mr. Boehm loves seeing the artwork that his students are creating and we do too!

COLLECTION EXTENDED THROUGH - Wednesday, April 29!

BCMS is working with the Somerville YMCA to help encourage and thank our local healthcare workers.

Write a thank you card, make a poster or create a work of art to show your gratitude for the healthcare workers at Robert Wood Johnson University Hospital in Somerville. These letters really motivate them to keep going. The Somerville YMCA will collect the letters, disinfect them and distribute them to healthcare professionals. Collection boxes will be placed outside of the BCMS main entrance the week of April 20th, Monday- Friday from 9am to 2pm where you can submit your projects.

The cards will be distributed to hospital staff next week.

post_text:
One school event that has not been canceled - the state finals of New Jersey History Day!

BCMS 8th grade students, Sean and Brendan qualified at the regional competition to represent BCMS at this event. Their exhibit, Conflict of the Orders, explains how the Plebeian class of Rome broke through social barriers to get democratic freedoms and rights that were denied to them by the Patrician class. It is constructed with Roman style pillars at the front and features twelve tablets from ancient Rome. Constructed of wood to support the weight of the display, this exhibit allows people to feel as though they are back in ancient Rome, Sean and Brendan not only learned about this ancient civilization, but also some makerspace-type carpentry to complete their outstanding display!

Their entry must be submitted by tomorrow, April 20 and awards are being given out virtually on May 4!

Good Luck at STATES Sean and Brendan!

Tomorrow's Board of Education meeting will be held remotely and live stream on our district's website https://www.branchburg.k12.nj.us/b_o_e/view_board_of_education_meetings_online beginning at 8:00pm.

Public comments are to be submitted via email to: publiccomment@branchburg.k12.nj.us and will be monitored during the meeting. Comments having to do with agenda items will be read during the first public comment and non agenda item comments will be read during the second public comment.

Please note:

Commenter's name and address (physical) must be included for us to read their comment into the record.

• Comments will be accepted anytime up to and during the meeting.

At Stony Brook 4th grade students participated in their seventh round of G.E.L. which focused on a fun enrichment activity that continued their discussion of kindness. Each year Google holds a contest to create a new “Google Doodle”, which is displayed on their homepage. The “doodle” is the word Google that is transformed in some way to reflect a theme. This year’s theme is “I Show Kindness By…” We began our lesson by discussing what images come to mind when they picture kindness. Mrs. Burke then led the students in an activity that had them practicing how to transform words by utilizing images to reflect a specific theme. Students were then given the word “Stony Brook” or “Kindness” to transform in order to display images that they associate with kindness.

Below is an example!

post_text:
BCMS 8th grade LA classes created podcast episodes to discuss the characters in their unit 1 book clubs that struggled with mental health or social issues. They were able to research, interview, and provide real life resources for others struggling with similar problems. Students were able to utilize school staff such Superintendent Gensel and BCMS guidance counselors, psychologists, and social workers to gather more information and add to the authenticity of their podcast episode. Not only did these students incorporate text evidence and analysis while discussing their book club characters, but they also made a real world connection to the serious mental health and social issues that young teens may struggle with today. Each episode was loaded onto the teacher created website to create our very own “Starcast Cafe Podcast Channel”. Students were able to listen to their peers episodes at the Starcast Cafe in the Glass Lab. The teachers were so proud, they even provided some hot cocoa for their learners.

This was a great educational experience!

post_text:
At BCMS in recognition of National School Violence Awareness Week, our Guidance Department held the second annual Principal’s Competition. This year’s school-wide competition focused on the theme - No Place for Hate.
The competition involved having students consider the question, “What is No Place for Hate” to them? Students were challenged to create a piece of artwork in a medium of choice, to write a poem or short story, to take a photograph, to write a rap or song or to create a music video . Students were encouraged to be as creative as they desired.
Our winners were treated to a pizza lunch with a friend in the Principal’s Conference Room and they were invited to present their work at the November 21, 2019 Board of Education meeting.

Congratulations to: Jessica, Christopher, Adriana , Katie, Gabrielle and Chase!

post_text: At Whiton, the 1st grade students in Mrs. Puzzo’s class are "word detectives". They have word detective kits that they can use to solve tricky words. The tools they use are a magnifying glass, highlighter strip, post-it notes, and an index card. Some strategies they have learned and practiced are looking closely at a word, doing a double check, checking all the parts of the word, and noticing when there is a problem and trying to fix it. They have completed many missions and solved lots of words!

post_text: At BCMS, Mrs. Puglisi’s Financial Literacy class had two guest speakers from a local bank come in to discuss some important money management tips. Using an online compound interest calculator, they showed the students the importance of beginning to save money while they’re young, even if it’s only $10 a month. They also went into detail about the importance of having a good credit score.
